{"id":"1411.2533","submitter":"Arnon Dar","authors":"Shlomo Dado and Arnon Dar","title":"A Common Solution of Two Cosmic Puzzles","comments":"Updated. Added references","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The origin of the diffuse extragalactic gamma-ray background, which was\nmeasured with the large area telescope (LAT) aboard the Fermi satellite at\nenergy below 820 GeV, and of the diffuse cosmic background of neutrinos, which\nwas observed at much higher energies with the IceCube detector deep under the\nsouth pole ice, are among the current unsolved major cosmic puzzles. Here we\nshow that their properties indicate a common origin: the decay of mesons\nproduced in collisions of cosmic rays accelerated in relativistic jets with\nmatter in/near source. Moreover, their properties are those expected if these\nhighly relativistic jets are those that produce long duration gamma ray bursts\nin core collapse supernovae of type Ic, which take place mostly in the densest\nregions of giant molecular clouds in star forming galaxies, and those that are\nfired by blazars into their broad line region (BLR), which contains millions of\nmini-clouds.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Nov 2014 18:50:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 3 Feb 2015 13:40:27 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 20 May 2015 17:09:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-21"}
